observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The Management to instruct the end-users that delivery of procured items must be through the GSO so that the required ICS or PAR are prepared before issuing the items to the them;
The General Services Office to –
Submit the PAR, if the same are prepared for the properties identified in Annex E, otherwise, issue the required ICS and submit a copy to this Office;
Not sign the Inspection and Acceptance Report if the items are not delivered to the GSO;
Ensure that all semi-expendable properties are properly supported with ICS;
Maintain the forms, registries, and reports (Semi-Expendable Property Card, Registry of Semi-Expendable Property Issued, Report of Semi-Expendable Property Issued, and Report on the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property) prescribed in COA Circular 2022-004 to strengthen the controls over the semi-expendable properties;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to -
Make the necessary adjusting journal entry/ies to correct the recording of the herein transactions;
Ensure that properties are recorded based on the cost per item to ensure that only the capitalizable items are recorded as part of the PPE.

We recommended the following:
The Management to –
Ensure that the programs, projects, activities are sufficiently detailed or specifically identified in the appropriation ordinance of the LGU;
Ensure that the budget is disbursed only for the specific purpose to which it was appropriated;
Ensure that a Program of Work is already prepared before the budget call to support the appropriation of the project;
The Municipal Budget Office and the Office of the Municipal Accountant to –
Reconcile the differences in the obligations and actual expenditures noted in Annex F;
Reconcile monthly the RAO and the records of the OMA;
The Municipal Budget Office to ensure that the appropriations are with specific identification, if not, ensure that before utilizing the budget in generic term, there is already a Sangguniang Bayan approval for the disbursements;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to –
After reconciliation with the records of the MBO, make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the cost of the properties of the LGU;
Make the following adjusting entries to correct the observation in no. 2 f:
(dr) CIP – Building & Other Structures		1,800,960.88
Construction of Slaughter House Phase II at Purok 5, Sagbayan
(cr) CIP -  Building & Other Structures		1,800,960.88
Slaughter House at Purok 7 Poblacion
Ensure that the disbursements for the projects are properly recorded in its corresponding Subsidiary Ledger;
Properly identify the disbursements for the projects e.g. whether it should be capitalizable or recorded only as expense;
The Municipal Engineering Office to –
Prepare individual Program of Works for the works to be done per property;
Ensure that the property is identified in the Program of Works so that the OMA can properly record the disbursements;
The General Services Office to issue Inventory Custodian Slips to the semi-expendable properties in item no.1.

We recommended to the management to instruct the Municipal Accountant to do the following:
Properly evaluate the existing balances in the Due to LGUs account;
Determine the proper action;
For completed PPAs prepare the necessary adjusting entries to drop the amounts from the Due to LGUs account and submit to the Office of the COA Auditor the approved Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) duly supported with working papers and other pertinent documents to justify the adjustments made;
For items to be liquidated, submit the liquidation report to the source agency, prepare the necessary adjustments in the books, and submit to the Office of the COA Auditor the approved Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) duly supported with transmittal letter stamped received by the source LGU;
For unremitted items, remit the balances to the concerned LGUs, record the remittance in the books, and submit to the Office of the COA Auditor the approved Disbursement Vouchers duly supported with working papers and other pertinent documents. In addition, remit any collections due to other local government units every month;
For unreconciled balances, coordinate with the implementing unit of the LGU or the source agencies for its utilization and reconciliation. If the source agency cannot be identified, determine the age of the balance and if it qualifies as dormant request for its write-off;
For unexpended balances and savings in the Trust Fund amounting to ₱109,516.69:
transfer the cash from the Trust Fund bank account to the General Fund bank account;
prepare an adjusting entry in the Trust Fund to record the transfer of funds from the Trust Fund to the General Fund using the following suggested entry:
Due to LGUs	xxx
Cash in Bank		xxx
prepare another adjusting entry in the General Fund to record the receipt of funds from the Trust Fund to the General Fund using the following suggested accounting entry:
Cash in Bank	xxx
Prior Period Adjustment	xxx
For unexpended balances and savings in the General Fund amounting to ₱3,616.46:
prepare an adjusting entry in the General Fund to transfer to the unappropriated surplus the balance in the Due to LGUs account amounting to ₱3,616.46 using the following suggested accounting entry:
Due to LGUs 	xxx
Prior Period Adjustment	xxx
For unexpended balances and savings in the General Fund and Trust Fund, submit to the Office of the COA Auditor the approved Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) duly supported with working papers and other pertinent documents to justify the adjustments made, and coordinate with the Municipal Budget Officer for the preparation of the Supplemental Budget;
For dormant balances, request for write-off of dormant accounts following the procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023.
For the succeeding transactions:
Evaluate all funds received before recording the same in the books of accounts so that only fund transfers from other local government units (LGUs) with specific purpose and funds received for remittance to LGUs are recorded in the Due to LGUs account. Funds transfers from national government agencies (NGAs) with specific purpose and funds received for remittance to NGAs may be recorded in the Due to NGAs account. While funds received without specific purpose may be recorded as Subsidy Income in the General Fund. Lastly, LGU counterparts may be recorded in the Trust Liabilities account.
Adjust the liabilities of the LGU as soon as fund transfers from other LGUs and NGAs have been liquidated or as soon as the purpose have been completed.
At the end of each year, evaluate whether savings exist and check pertinent agreements with the source agency as to the proper treatment of the unexpended amounts. If balances are required to be returned to the source agency, remit the unexpended funds to the source agency. Otherwise, revert the funds to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund of the LGU.

We recommended to the management to do the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to find the journal entry voucher (JEV) reversing the Deferred Special Education Tax account in the General Fund (GF) and submit the same supported with working papers and other pertinent documents to the Office of the COA Auditor for review;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile with the Municipal Treasurer, determine the total advance Special Education Taxes (SET) collections that are still deposited in the bank account of the General Fund, make the necessary adjusting entries to the Deferred Special Education Tax account and Due to Other Funds account of the GF as well as the Deferred Special Education Tax account and Due from Other Funds of the Special Education Fund (SEF);
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to transfer the advance SET collections from the GF bank account to the SEF bank account with duly approved Disbursement Voucher (DV) supported with working papers and other pertinent documents, record the transfer in the Cash in Bank cashbooks of the Municipal Treasurer and in the books of accounts of the LGU by reversing the Due to Other Funds account in the GF and Due from Other Funds account in the SEF, and submit the DV, JEVs, and supporting documents to the COA Auditor for review;
For the succeeding transactions:
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer and the collectors to record and deposit the current and advance Real Property Taxes in the General Fund and record the current and advance Special Education Taxes in the Special Education Fund;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly train his accounting bookkeepers in the proper accounting treatment of advance SETs and remind them to always refer to the accountable forms and the Report of Collections and Deposits in recording the collections and deposits of the LGU. Otherwise, hire an additional staff who possesses the necessary competence.

We recommended to the management to do the following:
Instruct the Local Finance Committee to make the necessary revisions to the Revenue Code and include provisions for the following:
Complete description and price of each type of interment package and other services and charges;
Mode and terms of payment;
Execution of contract of lease, contract to sell (for installment payments) or deed of absolute sale (upon full payment), whichever is applicable;
Grace period and remedies available to the LGU and the buyer;
Provision for a uniform application of the ordinance, whether employee of the LGU or not.
For existing payors:
Compel the payors with fully paid packages to execute a contract of lease or deed of absolute sale with the LGU in accordance to the provisions of the revised Revenue Code;
Compel the payors with unpaid balances to execute a contract of lease or contract to sell with the LGU in accordance to the provisions of the revised Revenue Code;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to issue demand letters to individuals with due but unpaid balances, otherwise, necessary civil actions will be instituted;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize the unrecorded receivables of ₱5,500,600.00, revenues of ₱2,250,600.00 and unearned income of ₱3,250,000.00 in the books of accounts of the LGU;
For subsequent transactions:
Instruct the cemetery in-charge to apply consistent and equally to all persons (whether employee of the LGU or not) the assessment and collection rules and procedures provided in the Revised Revenue Code;
Instruct the cemetery in-charge to keep a copy of all contracts relating to the lease or sale of interment packages and other cemetery fees and charges;
Instruct the cemetery in-charge to monitor the assessments and payments of new cemetery fees and charges, and prepare a monthly list of unpaid balances and submit the same to the Municipal Treasurer’s Office for proper action;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare demand letters as soon as the payments become due and demandable, impose penalties for delayed payments, and/or file the appropriate civil action in case of non-payment;
Instruct the cemetery in-charge to prepare a list of unpaid new cemetery fees and charges at year-end and submit the Municipal Accountant’s Office;
The management to determine the unit cost of the lot already sold and available for sale so that the necessary adjustments may be effected by the Office of the Municipal Accountant to the accounts “Prior Period Adjustment” (for sold lots) and “Inventory” (for available lots). The adjustments be supported with necessary documents and submitted to the audit team for verification.
The Municipal Accountant to establish and maintain special accounts for the expenditures related to the operations of new public cemetery.

We recommended the following:
The Local Chief Executive to –
Issue an Executive Order creating a Pre-repair inspection Committee and a Post-repair inspection Committee who shall be responsible for the inspection of the properties to be repaired and had been repaired, respectively;
Submit a copy, to the Office of the Auditor, of the Executive Order for the creation of the committees;
Instruct the Heads of Offices to follow the operating procedures provided above for the repairs and maintenance of vehicles and other properties of the LGU.
The General Services Office to –
Ensure that the Pre and Post Repair Inspection Reports are properly and completely accomplished especially the information that can be provided even if the documents for the vehicles are not yet completely compiled and the scope of the repairs is properly indicated;
Require the submission of waste materials and the Waste Materials Report from the end-users of the repaired vehicle;
Ensure that the repairs undertaken are recorded in repair history document of each vehicle;
Ensure that the waste materials are securely stored in the bodega of the LGU.
Prepare a report of all waste materials that was seen during site inspection and request to this office for its disposal;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to the Disbursements Vouchers before processing the payments.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Mayor to instruct the Heads of Offices to follow the correct procurement procedures and to properly and completely fill-up the Purchase Request.
The Bids and Awards Committee to –
Prepare the Annual Procurement Plan (APP) based on GPPB Circular 07-2015 and to take note on the Definition provided in the template of the APP for its preparation;
Consolidate all homogenous items requested for purchase into one procurement activity so that the correct mode of procurement will be undertaken and to avoid multiple procurements;
Change the template of the Request for Price Quotations and include necessary instruction to bidders, such PhilGEPS Registration number and whether partial bid is allowed
Ensure that the Purchase Orders are properly and completely filled-up;
The General Services Office to –
check the Purchase Orders against the delivery receipts and charged invoice to ensure that only the items in the Purchase Orders are delivered and paid;
Provide proof that the hanging cabinet that was not in the delivery receipt was delivered, otherwise, a Notice of Disallowance will be issued.
Provide explanation as to the disbursement with different items in the delivery receipt and charge invoice, if the explanation is unacceptable, a Notice of Suspension will be issued.
Issue Inventory Custodian Slips for curtains and steel cabinet (see remarks in the Annex O)
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to ensure that Disbursements Vouchers are supported with the required supporting documents.

We recommended the following:
The Management to –
Instruct the concerned offices to submit the required documents marked “N” in  Annex P, specifically the Official/Collection Receipt or Charge Invoice, Delivery Receipt, Activity Design and Attendance Sheets, otherwise a Notice of Suspension will be issued by the audit team;
Stop allocating budget for Representation Expenses, unless there are international delegation that needs to be attended by the Municipal officials, provided further that the same are duly approved by the President of the Philippines;
Subsequently, ensure that the necessary documents to support the disbursements for meals and snacks and other disbursements of the LGU are properly and completely attached to the Disbursement Vouchers;
The Municipal Budget Office to not process any Request for Obligations if the program or activity is not clearly identified in the Annual Budget and if there is no Approved Activity Design;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to not process the Disbursements Vouchers for payment if the same is not completely supported with the required documents;
The Bids and Awards Committee to ensure that –
the Purchase Request provides the necessary specifications/details of the items to be procured;
the Request for Price Quotations and Purchase Orders provide the necessary specifications or brand (if applicable) of the items to be supplied by the supplier;
The General Service Office to not sign IAR for items that they have not accepted.

We recommended to the management to –
Instruct the HRMO to –
Recompute the wages of the job orders, those in Annex Q, who were incorrectly paid their daily rate, and for any excess payment thereof must be refunded by the concerned JO;
Submit a duly certified copy of Appointments for the identified job orders listed in Annex R;
Submit the lacking Travel Orders and Certificate of Appearance, marked “No” in Annex S, otherwise, a corresponding Notice of Suspension or Disallowance will be issued;
Issue a new appointment for a job order once there is a change in the daily rate, and avoid erasures thereof, to ensure that this was duly approved by the concerned officials;
Ensure that the “conforme” portion in the appointment was signed with printed name of the JO;
Ensure that all Job Order appointments are signed by the Municipal Mayor even if the JO are assigned in the Office of the Sanggunian Bayan;
Ensure that the Certificate of Assumption of the Job Orders were signed by them and their respective Heads of Office;
Ensure that Accomplishment Reports are properly filled-up and signed by the JO and the concerned Head of Office;
Ensure that travels outside the Municipality for official purposes are supported with a properly accomplished and approved travel order and certificate of appearance. Also, indicate in the travel order whether the travel is with or without travel allowance; For team/capacity building activities, it is sufficient that the Head of Office signs the CA;
Ensure that if the JO is out of its official station, but within the LGU, doing its assigned task, it is supported with a duly accomplished and approved locator slip;
Ensure that when the JO is out of its official station for personal reason, it is supported with a duly accomplished and approved “Pass Slip;”
The Management to –
After the HRMO recomputes the wages of the job orders in Annex Q,  pay the correct wages due them;
Avoid designating to a job order a function not assignable to them. Instead, assign it to a qualified regular employee of the LGU, otherwise, the Management may hire through Contract of Service provided that the job is not part of the regular functions of the agency and the engagement of the service is subject to pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184 and its implementing guidelines;
Limit the travels of the job orders only for (a) undertaking official missions/tasks which cannot be performed by/or assigned to other any regular/permanent official and/or employee of the agency, and/or (b) performing tasks/activities necessary to be able to fulfill the obligations as contained in his/her contract of service.
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the disbursements for payroll are completely supported with the required supporting documents.

The Management to instruct the Municipal Accountant Office and the General Services Office to reconcile its records starting CY 2023 in order to show the correct balances of the PPE accounts of the Municipality;

The General Services Office to submit to the Municipal Accountant Office the Inventory Report of Vehicles as of December 31, 2023 and every year thereafter;

The MACCO and the GSO to –
Reconcile the accounting records with the inventory report starting calendar year 2023 and every year thereafter;

Once the unrecorded machinery and transportation equipment are identified, coordinate for the retrieval of documents in order that the correct cost is recorded in the books of the LGU (since the cost reflected in Annex B is based on GSO records only and some do not have cost);

The Municipal Accountant Office to –

Make the necessary journal entries to correct the balances of the affected accounts and submit the same together with working papers and supporting documents;

Start maintaining the PPE Ledger Cards or ensure that the recording in the ECPAC accounting software is sufficient to identify the machinery or transportation equipment and may be used in the reconciliation with the GSO inventory report.

We also recommend to the Management to undertake the one-time cleansing of the Municipality’s Property, Plant and Equipment account by following the guidelines set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 in order that the PPE account of the LGU becomes reliable and verifiable.

The Municipal Budget Office to –

Start using the appropriate RAAO in controlling the appropriations and obligations of each expenditure;

Ensure that all charges against the 5% LDRRMF are properly and completely recorded in the RAAO;

Ensure that Obligation Requests are properly coded to avoid confusion and erroneous recording in the MACCO;

Ensure that only the expenses with Obligation Requests duly signed by the LDRRMO are charged against the LDRRMF.


The Municipal Accountant Office to –

Make the necessary journal entries, supported with working papers, to correct the accounts affected by the incomplete and erroneous recording of the disbursements charged against the LDRRMF, and submit the same to this office;

Ensure that the transactions/disbursements are recorded in the proper accounts.

The MBO and MACCO to do monthly reconciliation of its records in order that the correct amount of unspent LDRRMF is recorded in the books of accounts of the LGU;

The LDRRMO to indicate the correct source of fund in the DV and/or ObRe so that the disbursements are correctly processed and charged to the appropriate fund.

The Municipal Accountant Office to -

Make the necessary journal entries, supported with working papers, to correct the accounts affected by the foregoing observations, and submit the same to this office;

Ensure that the transactions are properly recorded in the correct fund.

The Municipal Budget Office to stop processing disbursements that are chargeable against the Trust Fund;

The LDRRMO to indicate the correct source of fund in the Disbursement Vouchers and/or ObRe so that the disbursements are correctly processed and charged to the appropriate fund.

The Management to –

Instruct the designated custodian of the cabinet to ensure that the cabinet is always locked and Accountable Forms are secured from theft and/or unauthorized withdrawals;

Instruct the designated custodian of the permanent record books for accountable forms to ensure that all receipts, withdrawals, returns, cancellations, and issuances of Accountable Forms are duly recorded in the record books and to follow the correct format as prescribed by the Local Treasury Operations Manual;

Instruct the Accountable Officers to prepare a Requisition and Issue Voucher (RIV) to support their request for withdrawal of Accountable Forms;

Instruct the respective Accountable Officers to immediately remit to the Liquidating Officer their balances of accountability for accountable forms which have already been issued as of cut-off (September 18, 2023) as well as its corresponding the collections; and

Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to conduct an investigation in order to locate the missing Accountable Forms and provide the COA Auditor with a copy of the results of the investigation.

The Management to –

Investigate as to the whereabouts of the unaccounted Accountable Forms and to immediately remit to the LO together with the cash and/or check collections if found already issued, or to present to the COA Auditor for review and verification if found unused;

Require the Accountable Officers to review the entries in the E-TRACS made by their staff for receipts, issuances, and returns of accountable forms in order to ensure that all accountable forms are completely accounted for;

Require the Accountable Officers to prepare monthly RAAF and submit the same to the designated MTO personnel for consolidation into CRAAF;

Require the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to submit the monthly RAAFs and CRAAF to the COA Auditor not later than the fifth (5th) day of the ensuing month as required by LTOM.

The Management and the General Services Officer to -

Issue Property Acknowledgement Receipts for the 39 serviceable motor vehicles of the Municipality;

After repair of the motor vehicles with “under repair” status in Annex A, issue also a PAR for said vehicles;

Ensure that the person receiving the motor vehicle is properly bonded (Section 101 of PD 1445);

Keep intact and complete records of the PARs; and

Renew the PAR every three years or every time there is a change in custodianship/user of the property.

The General Services Officer to –

Prioritize the renewal of all vehicles with expired registration;

Keep the original copies of OR and CR of the vehicles;

Ensure that all the vehicles of the Municipality have an updated vehicle registration;

Gather all the documents relevant to the ownership of the garbage compactor and one motorcycle so that it may be registered under the name of the Municipality, if warranted.

The Management to - 

Designate the General Services Officer as a Special Disbursing Officer for the purpose of vehicle registration renewal;

Instruct the vehicle drivers to remind the GSO that the registration of the vehicle is near its expiration so that the office may process the renewal of its registration.

The Management to –

Ensure that the government vehicles are assigned to bonded officials;

To choose one from the following:

Assign vehicle to the head of office but not to pay the commutable TA;

Pay the commutable TA but will not assign vehicle to the head of office; or

Pay the commutable TA but with corresponding deduction if the head of office used a government vehicle;

Ensure that the payment for RATA is supported with complete prescribed documents.

The Management to –

Request from the Municipal Sanggunian Bayan for an SB Resolution allowing reimbursement of communication expenses specifying the office, designation, and rates that may be allowed;

Ensure that all payments for communication expenses are supported with complete supporting documents before payments are made.

The management to instruct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to do the following:

Submit the herein-identified lacking supporting documents to the contract;

Use the updated checklist of documentary requirements for contract review;

Diligently follow the procurement procedures as prescribed by law, rules and regulations, and other relevant issuances;

Carefully and thoroughly check the information, tenor, terms and conditions contained in the Bidding Documents before approving and distributing the same to the prospective bidders; and

Carefully and thoroughly evaluate the Bidding Documents submitted by the prospective bidders, otherwise, contracts executed by the LGU with the winning bidders who submitted Bidding Documents (Legal, Technical, and Financial Aspects) with errors, deficiencies and misrepresentations may be declared void and without effect;

Impose proper sanctions on non-compliant bids, otherwise, the BAC may be held liable for passing a deficient bid.

The management to instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to:

Henceforth, ensure that an Appropriation Ordinance is already enacted before certifying that there is an available appropriation for the disbursement;

Follow existing laws, rules and regulations on the savings, realignment and augmentation of funds.

The Municipal Accountant’s Office to –

Adhere to the recording requirements of the NGAS for the Real Property and Special Education Tax by following the pro-forma accounting entries under Sec. 36 Volume 1 of the Manual on New Government Accounting System;

Make the necessary adjustments to correct the balance of the Deferred Real Property and Special Education Tax, Due to LGUs and Real Property Tax Receivable; 

Stop recording advance payments for realty taxes as a “Due to LGUs” in the Trust Fund books of accounts, instead record it as Deferred Real Property Tax in the General Fund and Deferred Special Education Tax in the Special Education Fund books of accounts.

Submit the journal entry vouchers together with the working papers and supporting documents to this office for further review and verification; and 

Record in its proper accounts the discounts and penalties related to collections of realty taxes.  

The Municipal Treasurer’s Office to –

Include in the report submitted to the MACCO the discounts given and penalties imposed and collected so that the MACCO can record the same in its proper accounts;

Reconcile with the MACCO its records and reports in order for the MACCO to correct the affected accounts.

The Municipal Engineer’s Office to:

Submit report to the Municipal Budget Office that the projects under items 2 and 3 are completed physically since part of the area was concreted by the DPWH in its road widening project;

Follow-up the laborer for the project in item 4 to complete the project;

Ensure that construction materials are used for its intended purpose;

Coordinate with the Municipal Budget Office for the budget and status of the implementation of the project in order that completed projects with balances may be reverted and used, through Supplemental Budget, for another 20% Development Fund projects.

The Municipal Budget Office to –

Request for the reversion of the unobligated balance of completed projects in items 2 and 3, upon receipt of the report from the Municipal Engineer’s Office, and have it appropriated, through a Supplemental Budget, for 20% DF projects.

Ensure that the additional appropriation for items 1 and 5 are properly monitored so that charges thereof are for its intended purpose.

Instruct the GSO and Heads of the end-user units to provide the BAC with historical data of the LGU’s and the end-user units’ monthly fuel consumption in order to facilitate the in the conduct of meticulous planning and scheduling of procurement activities for the purchase of fuel;

Instruct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to:

properly include the procurement of fuel in the LGU’s APP based on the results of a meticulous and judicious planning supported by historical data;

procure all fuel requirements of the LGU in bulk through Public Bidding except those that meet the conditions for Direct Retail Purchase;

Instruct the GSO to:

read and follow the procedures in fuel consumption under pertinent issuances especially those prescribed under the Manual on Audit of Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles;

impose stringent controls on fuel consumption by serially numbering the Driver’s Trip Tickets and withdrawal slips, and ensuring that collated Driver’s Trip Tickets, withdrawal slips and charge invoices are completely filled-up indicating relevant data, most especially, the plate number of the vehicle;

 diligently prepare and issue the reports required for fuel consumption, as follows:

Monthly Report of Official Travels;

Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

discontinue processing disbursements for fuel not yet delivered by fuel suppliers;

ensure that required supporting documents are attached to the disbursement vouchers and are completely filled-up;

discontinue processing payments for fuel reimbursements unless it complies with the conditions of Direct Retail Purchase;

ensure that no reimbursements for fuel are included in the claim for travelling expenses;

Instruct the Heads of the end-user units to closely monitor their fuel consumption and avoid consumption beyond their office’s budget; 

Assign a liaison officer for the whole LGU to deliver and pick-up documents to conserve fuel; and
Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to avoid charging fuel expenses against the budget for traveling expenses.

Instruct the concerned employees to refund the amount under the column “Over Payment” in Appendix H for excess of actual travel expense paid over the allowable travel expenses and submit a copy of official receipt proving that the over-payment was already refunded;

Submit the lacking documents enumerated in Appendix H and the invoices for IT with claims for reimbursement for fuel;

Instruct the Accounting Office to recompute the total amount reflected in the itinerary of travel of each individual claim based on the source documents before processing the payment to avoid over-payments; and

Instruct the Accounting Office to ensure that all documentary requirements are complete and attached to the vouchers or payrolls before processing any claims for traveling expenses.

The requisitioning unit, upon withdrawal of the supplies and materials for project implementation, to prepare the Requisition and Issue Slip so that withdrawal, issuance and transfer of accountability may properly take place;

The GSO to prepare and submit, monthly, the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (together with the RIS) as basis of the Accounting Office in recording its utilization in the proper expense or asset account; and

The GSO to conduct inventory to have reconciliation of its records with that of the MACCO.

We recommended to the management to require:

a. The Chairman of the Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to prepare and maintain an Inventory of all Local Roads and a road map. Likewise, ensure the preparation of the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network (RPCLRN) at least annually;

b. The General Services Officer to prepare and maintain a Report on Local Road Network (RLRN) and keep a complete LRN Property Card for all roads and its component;

c. The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

d. The Municipal Accountant to provide adjusting journal entries, if warranted, duly supported with the working paper on the distribution of costs to recognize changes upon completion of the required inventory reports and reconciliation with the Registry of Public Infrastructure, if there is one. Moreover, depreciation shall be adjusted and provided accordingly duly supported with the lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component; and

e. The Municipal Accountant to disclose the total road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements of the LGU in the prescribed form as required in Annex B of COA Circular 2015-002.

We recommended the following:
The Management to instruct the Municipal Accountant Office and the General Services Office to reconcile its records starting CY 2023 in order to show the correct balances of the PPE accounts of the Municipality;
The General Services Office to submit to the Municipal Accountant Office the Inventory Report of Vehicles as of December 31, 2023 and every year thereafter;
The MACCO and the GSO to –
Reconcile the accounting records with the inventory report starting calendar year 2023 and every year thereafter;
Once the unrecorded machinery and transportation equipment are identified, coordinate for the retrieval of documents in order that the correct cost is recorded in the books of the LGU (since the cost reflected in Annex G is based on GSO records only and some do not have cost);
The Municipal Accountant Office to –
Make the necessary journal entries to correct the balances of the affected accounts and submit the same together with working papers and supporting documents;
Start maintaining the PPE Ledger Cards or ensure that the recording in the ECPAC accounting software is sufficient to identify the machinery or transportation equipment and may be used in the reconciliation with the GSO inventory report.
We also recommend to the Management to undertake the one-time cleansing of the Municipality’s Property, Plant and Equipment account by following the guidelines set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 in order that the PPE account of the LGU becomes reliable and verifiable.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Budget Office to –
Start using the appropriate RAAO in controlling the appropriations and obligations of each expenditure;
Ensure that all charges against the 5% LDRRMF are properly and completely recorded in the RAAO;
Ensure that Obligation Requests are properly coded to avoid confusion and erroneous recording in the MACCO;
Ensure that only the expenses with Obligation Requests duly signed by the LDRRMO are charged against the LDRRMF.
The Municipal Accountant Office to –
Make the necessary journal entries, supported with working papers, to correct the accounts affected by the incomplete and erroneous recording of the disbursements charged against the LDRRMF, and submit the same to this office;
Ensure that the transactions/disbursements are recorded in the proper accounts.
The MBO and MACCO to do monthly reconciliation of its records in order that the correct amount of unspent LDRRMF is recorded in the books of accounts of the LGU;
The LDRRMO to indicate the correct source of fund in the DV and/or ObRe so that the disbursements are correctly processed and charged to the appropriate fund.

We recommended the following -
The Municipal Accountant Office to –
Make the necessary journal entries, supported with working papers, to correct the accounts affected by the foregoing observations, and submit the same to this office;
Ensure that the transactions are properly recorded in the correct fund.
The Municipal Budget Office to stop processing disbursements that are chargeable against the Trust Fund;
The LDRRMO to indicate the correct source of fund in the Disbursement Vouchers and/or ObRe so that the disbursements are correctly processed and charged to the appropriate fund.

We recommended to the management to do the following:
Instruct the designated custodian of the cabinet to ensure that the cabinet is always locked and Accountable Forms are secured from theft and/or unauthorized withdrawals;
